reply_content:
@Ashleyunfiltered I mean, first of all, you took their opinion way too personally. Secondly, I know tonnes of people who call their step kids their kids. It's not actually that uncommon. Even so, the person you're responding to has a point that this documentary is clearly heavily edited. You have no idea what else was said (by both sides might I add), and the fact that they included how many times she called herself their mother feels extremely deliberate on the producer's part.

Look at tiger king. Probably the best case and example to use for how editing plays a huge part in spinning a narrative. The entire world hated Carol even though she was far from the worst of them. 10 minutes on google had me debunking half the shit that was put in the doco about her, including how "run down" and poorly maintained the tiger cages were. Her cages were not only bigger than the others, but they were maintained better too? She was also the only one in the whole doco that admitted she had done wrong in the past and learned from it, none of the others did that. There was a literal sexual predator on the show, and yet Carol was hated by what felt like the entire world. 

People need to realise that documentaries DO NOT need to be unbiased or completely truthful to be released. They're movies and for entertainment, they're allowed to put their own spin or perspective on things, and they do it in such a way you think you're getting the full story, but you're not. You're getting the producer's story. They're not for educational purposes, otherwise you'd be getting readings from academic literature and the investigation itself. I have a background in criminology, this is 101 shit. As much as I love true crime as the next person, fans get way too caught up in documentaries as if they just heard all the evidence laid out for them.

